76561198047688212,Recommended,238750,21588878,"Posted: 2 March, 2016",all,region lock dota,"This game pays homage to Might and Magic 1-5 and persoanlly, I like it very much.The good:* Unlike a lot of RPGs today, the combat mechanics are deep and srategic. Should you spend a turn healing and defending or should you take a chance and forgo healing this round to dish out damage with the hope of quickly ending the encounter? Decisions like these make combat satisfying.* Pretty graphics - Bright vibrant colours and nice character models.* Party based RPG that allows for a ton of customization options and increases re-play value.The bad:* Not enough content - The game is a lot of fun, but very short. The DLC addresses this nicely, but even so, the original should have been longer.* The storyline is not very memorable. I still vividly remember the story of Might and Magic 7, but despite having 244 play hours on MMX, I still can't recall the story."
,Recommended,238750,25028423,"Posted: 20 August, 2016",all,BasiukTV,"Decent Might & Magic game, nothing special, but fans of the series should enjoy it.Game is rather short & doesn't have whole lot of content, but it delivers good immersion and satisfying feeling of nostalgia :)I liked combats & skills system, and those two things are probably most important ones not to screw up in an RPG. I have low demands for graphics & music, so it's hard to dissapoint me there.All downsides for me were already summarized under ""not whole lot of content"". Not too many classes to select from, story plot is short, not too many cities to visit, not too many monsters to fight, not too many spells to learn, skills to train and quests to complete ... some cherished parts from earlier games are missing entirely (card game, killing traps, potion making). But what content provided, is of good quality.To summarize, game is worth playing, but probably has zero replay value, and that tells you something."
,Recommended,238750,16242534,"Posted: 7 June, 2015",all,Dreamshade,"As someone who has not played any other M&M titles, I can recommend this game.I would recommend playing this on the harder difficulty. This forces you to explore everywhere in order to level up, and will greatly reward you for searching every nook and cranny.This game has one interesting niche that sets it apart from other games, everything is finite. There are no respawning monsters, no respawning loot etc. This creates a sense of meaningfulness to every choice you make, when you spend your gold or sell equipment. Because of the way the game is set up you'll often run into enemies that are far too hard for you, or bosses you can't handle yet. I consider this a positive, as it encourages you to explore the world more in order to gear up / level up.If you read other reviews pros and cons, I would agree with most of them. However , this game stands out from other turn based RPG's so much, that I can't help but recommend it. I would love to see a M&M X-2 style game, improving upon it's strengths, and adding more customizability.Pick it up on sale. I'd value it around 15-20$."
,Recommended,238750,9021965,"Posted: 8 February, 2014",all,chaosblade,"For anyone who is a fan of the older Might and Magic games, Especially the really older ones (1-5), This game is a treat - and a blast from the past - IF you can set aside a few differences.Namely, The size/scale of the game. Don't expect a huge MM6-8 style world with hundreds of side quests - The world is much smaller and the plot is quite simple. Despite that, The loading times might annoy you and it's still a bit buggy. The skill system works a bit differently as well. But other than that..It has the spirit and feel of an MM game. I'd say it's well worth the price and Limbic should be commended for capturing NWC's spirit in this game as well. Hopefully, Next time, Ubisoft will consider a more large-scale MM game.And even if you aren't an MM fan.. This is a pretty nice RPG in today's standards, Giving well over 40-50 hours of entertaining gameplay."
,Recommended,238750,8919543,"Posted: 31 January, 2014",all,George Bashington,"Damn, this game gave me a headache. Should I recommend it or not? Is it, in the end, a good or a bad game?Well it is both. You're welcome. ;)In fact, MMX is a great old-school RPG, and some might hate it. If you don't like turn-based games, forget about it right away. It will appeal mostly to people who started playing computer games in the 80's and 90's. This said, this category of gamers will regret going back to another feature that was typical of the era: infinite loading times. This is, by far, the most annoying thing in this great game. You'll have to suffer long loadings every two minutes, because it makes you travel a lot, and reload saved games a lot. It is, apparently, very badly programed and suffers from huge stuttering issues on any machine. It runs ""smoother"" on 64-bit systems but doesn't really take advantage of huge amounts of memory as it could. Maybe it emulates floppy disks, I don't know. Let's call it a feature. Oh, and the world looks more like a maze than like an open world, making it difficult to find your way, even if you've discovered every square inch of land (or sea). If you were used to rushing from west to east in a matter of seconds in the old MM series (by tapping arrow keys madly, like Stakanov), you'll be disappointed by how long it takes to travel. It expands the world size artificially, but it works eventually.Now that's all for the bad stuff.Good things about this game? Mainly all the rest. First thing first, it is DIFFICULT. You'll spend hours trying to find the few roads/places where you're safe enough to gain some experience while avoiding dying every minute. Then you'll come back to places that were previously unaccessible to your party and kick some♥♥♥♥♥♥ Or not, and die again. And again. More often than in the old games, except maybe MM6 which was very open and very difficult too.You'll soon discover that you have to make careful choices in your skills, for every character in the party. At first, you'll also be poor as hell, which means that you'll have a hard time training your party while in the meantime healing it, buying new stuff and potions, identifying loot, etc. And then, half way from the end, you'll have not to care about money anymore since you'll have a good 100 k that will never be spent.But don't be fooled: money is one of your problems at first, but not the only one. Money will not buy you extraordinary items that can save your♥♥♥♥♥♥ It will help, but it is not the solution to all your problems. Exploration is much more rewarding than shopping, and as soon as two of your party members will be equiped with fine stuff, things will get easier. A few relics later and you'll be able to deal enough damage to cyclops. Yeeha!Then, there's magic. Remember the title, Might & Magic? Right, you'll need both. All the time. You'll need healing all the time, and above all, good warding spells. With good loot and a good spellcasting timing, you can take on almost any mob - if you're lucky. Yes, luck counts a lot. On the good side, it allows you to do critical damage. On the bad side, so it does for monsters. So you might litteraly obliterate a monster to 10% of its health, then it will do a beautiful critical strike and kill two party members in one blow. And they will not benefit from the experience gained from the fight...Now, should you reload or deal with it and visit a temple ASAP? It's all up to you. You can try again until only your party makes huge amounts of damage, or play fair. You can think hard about a specific puzzle's logic and finally understand how it works, or you can try any combination until the damn chest opens. You can take notes (real notes, on paper) or look for answers on the internet. Play fair and suffer a lot or play safe and... suffer a lot, but a bit less.This game rewards people who like exploring, and who are willing to come back to the same place they died a dozen times before just to see if now, it might be ok. And yes! It opens a new area. Now I can die again! Oh God, now I remember how loud I yelled at my computer in 1994, and why. And I also remember why I kept on playing. Damn, it's good.BUT PLEASE DO SOMETHING ABOUT THE LOADING TIMES."
