76561198195398514,Not Recommended,238750,35055752,Posted: 18 September,all,smithys_son,"***WARNING, SPOILERS***TL;DR: Lifelong fan says buy some of the older games and play them from GoG, not this one.Long story: I've been a fan of the series since I was born, I've beat MM6 (and loved it), MM7 (and loved it) and MM8 (and loved it), I tried this game hoping for another one of those three (I didn't play 9, but I've heard enough to not want to, I might eventually try it, but as of time of writing, I have not) but too much was changed, the forced grid sucked (angles were a lifesaver in the games I've played, rotate your party right and they have cover, but your enemies are wide open) also, the freedom of the earlier games was destroyed by the forced grid here, the way time passed only when you move from space to space was flowbreaking for me, for lack of a better word.The last stand approach to combat (Locking you in place if you're in melee range of a hostile) was again, horrible, part of the old fun was being able to run back into town, almost dead, trailing an army of angry monsters, sleep and heal in the inn, then go rejoin the fray alongside the guards.And (I may be remembering this wrong because I stopped caring) but it was forced turn based combat, DISCLAIMER: I like turn based combat and in fact, Love D&D and other turn based games, BUT, that's not Might and Magic, In the other games I mentioned, it was a crutch until you figured out the combat (or got specific endgame weapon & spell combos) and it was useful to take a minute so you can breathe and strategize, I used it almost all game (again, endgame combos shut down TBC) but you could always switch it to whatever worked as you needed, It just feels odd to me.Finally, (and this is more of a issue with Ubisoft than this game) the universe is new, different, and NOT, Might and Magic, Might and Magic has aliens, blasters, robots, and space ships, the gods are kept vague (I don't remember any ever being named) this new universe has none of that as far as I can tell. The Ironfists are gone, The Kreegans are gone, The Ancients are gone, (and this already happened but...) the planet Enroth is gone. I don't mean that these things are destroyed (Except Enroth...) None of them ever happened, all that rich lore from games 1-9? all that stuff from Heroes 1-4? Never. Happened.So, to bring an end to my long rant, don't buy this, the older games might not have the best graphics, but they have the heart, soul, and fun this game never will have.The only positive thing I can say for this is that I got Might and Magic 6 with it, but even then, I should have bought it from GoG for (about) $5 less.Edit(s): Fixed typos"
76561198030982961,Recommended,238750,20840196,"Posted: 29 January, 2016",all,Inictus,"Love this game. If you are a fan of old school turn based grid movement games, get this. Many have a problem with UPlay. If this is not a problem for you - and you love old school turn based games - just get it already."
76561198031827488,Recommended,238750,20497905,"Posted: 12 January, 2016",all,suntory_time,"The mixed reviews put me off this game for a long while, but I finally picked it up and was pleasantly suprised. I'm a die-hard fan of Might and Magic VI, which I've gone back and played several times over the years. This installment lacks the scope of VI, but captures the spirit of it.Planning and developing your party is the main highlight, despite a few minor issues with how skills are distributed across classes. Although there are party combinations that are clearly ""better"" if you are optimizing, there are lots of possibilities that are doable and fun, even by just using different skill distributions amongst the same classes.You have to accept that you can't get everything you want on every character or every party, since there is an effective limit on the experience you can gain in the game. This can be frustrating, but forces you build more intelligently and make sacrifices to get the skills you want. The game itself is somewhat linear and lacking in the open-world feel of other Might and Magic games. The story isn't very deep or compelling, similar to Heroes VI.The grid movement and turn-based combat are off-putting at first, but they ultimately created interesting opportunities for tactical gameplay. Combats are often repetitive although there are some variations in tactics based on the specific enemies. After beating it on the normal difficulty, I immediately played through again with a new party on the ""Warrior"" difficulty, which provided a fun challenge that felt like a different game, at least in the early going. Even after beating it again, I still find myself brainstorming different party combinations I want to try.Overall, not an ""amazing"" game, but quite enjoyable, with good replayability. Certainly better than the average review indicates. Now I'm primed to go back and play VI again."
