,Recommended,238750,24712824,"Posted: 4 August, 2016",all,weatherseed,"Allow me to cover something important in this review. Limbic Entertainment, the developers of this and the two most recent Heroes of Might and Magic games, is comprised of fans of the series. Their care and attention was plainly seen in H6, a game which was hated by many fans and, yet, still very good. Many new elements were added for better or worse and Limbic was not afraid of testing new ideas. Something the series has gone without since H3.This game, however, is product of the negative feedback from H6 on two fronts. The first is Ubisoft investing less money into this title. The second is Limbic's decision to play things safer this time. The decision to return to simpler mechanics wasn't a bad one. The game does suffer for the lack of time, money, and innovation it received.At the end of the day, they took all of the advancements from M&M7, slapped them on to M&M4, gave it a fresh coat of paint and called it a day. Not a bad game, just not a noteworthy one."
,Recommended,238750,8841415,"Posted: 25 January, 2014",all,Marcelo Sampaio,"Ok, being a fan of the Might and Magic games, I felt completelly abandoned... MM9 was a disaster... so rushed, so bugged that sold poorly. So poorly that it was the main responsible for 3DO's demise.Then, 10 years later, they announce a new Might and Magic. Its not made by Jon Van Caneghem, and its OBVIOUSLY not made by 3DO. Still... is this the  game I've waited 10 years for? Short answer is NO. Where's our open wold? All MMs featured fully open worlds, where the only barrier iour courage to tackle stronger enemies. In MMX, you have to clear one area to be able to go to the next!Then there's my second issue with this game: where's the enemy respawn? All MMs have some form of enemy respawn, which enables you to develop your characters as much as you want! Remember the enemy lairs in Might and Magic 3-5, that if you don't destroy, the area will repopulate within a few mounths? Its GONE in here.  No respawn means that there's a cap to how much you can level in each area, and considering how linear this game is, this means that if a boss is too tough for you, you can't just go to another areas to level up some more!The developers PPROMISSED respawning enemies, and thats one of the reasons I bought the early access. Then again Ubisoft also promissed a real modular game, yet never said that we need to BUY a 1,500 dollars software to be able to create MODs for it! They also never said that 32-bit users would get a capped experience. Heck, the early access worked perfectly on 32-bit OSs. Why they changed it?On the other hand, not everything in this game is bad. The graphics (if you have a 64-bit OS) are actually decent, with some beautifull landscapes and amazingly animated enemies. The sounds are great: sound effects are realistic, the voices are actually good, and each place has some very realistic ambient sounds (birds when you are near a forest, loud people when you are in a town, etc).The gamepay is surprinsingly good. They decided to make this game very old-scool, so they opted to use tile-based movement and turn-based battles. I like this in RPGs, it gives the game a more strategic feel. Most boss battles actually requires you to THINK before acting, and if you just randomly attack, you'll die in VERY few turns. The interface, on the other hand, isn't as limited as most games of our youth. While you can still use your spellbook to select spells and abilities, now you can use a very handy numbered action bar, and activate each action with the numeric keys. Believe-me it helps. There's even the ability to set map notes, something that we would LOVE back in the day.The game isn't very long though. Its one of the shortest MMs (only MM8 feels shorter than this one), but don't expect to beat it in a few hours. We are looking at a 40+ hours journey here, more if you select the hardest mode (yeah, you have a difficulty selector in here).Anyway, this isn't as good as I was expecting. The lack of enemy respawns makes mea bit angry, and the fact that they decided to break the game into acts is ridiculous! Still, this is a 7/10 game. Really, I'm a bit disappointed at this game, and i'm a HUGE fan of World of Xeen and Isles of Terra... Still, its a worthy game to carry the Might and Magic name.Now, lets just hope the modding community can fix this game, right?The good:+Graphics are actually good, and the sounds are amazing;+The turn-based and tile-based gameplay is back, and its great!!+Gameplay is great;+The classes are varied and nice to use;+The enemy models are very detailed, and have a very smooth movement;+Great dungeons, some are actually quite big;+The enemies actually look nice.The bad:-Graphics aren't as good if you use a 32-bit OS, and the voices are GONE.-The classes are not well balanced;-The game starts out too linear, and has been divided into ACTs;-There's NO enemy respawn, not even optional like the older MMs."
