76561198040367630,Not Recommended,238750,4651980,"Posted: 21 August, 2013",all,Wolfman,"So, now that the game is in full, lets get down to the♥♥♥♥♥♥and grits of the game.  What is wrong with it? And what is right with it?  Well.. currently, I am engaging in a full playthrough.  In my first 30 minutes, I discovered that the game seems to require MUCH more system resources than it should for the type of game you are playing.  The game also seems to take several steps BACKWARDS!! in regards to the progress that has been made in the dungeon Crawler genre of games.  It makes a sort of Dated, modern take on a familiar genre that has had leaps and bounds of progress made, 10 years ago.It may get better later... but currently, it clearely shows dated mechanics that I would have expected a company like Ubisoft to invest in improving (IE full voice overs, a fully explorable world) if they actually believed in the project.Currently, SOME of the main quest givers actually speak, and the game moves in a old school (and I mean super old school) grid method which is dated even for the 90s.  The game runs poorly which is honestly unforgiveable.  And last but not least, it just seems limiting in regards to the way you make your party.  That last one is a minor gripe, but I am in a nit picky mood at the time of this review.So what does the game do right?  Well, currently it seems very balanced, and the game is full of lore if you do not mind reading.  The story ties in with a familiar world (thus far) if you have been paying attention to the previous games in the series, and even comes with several nods to those games.  It isn't a terrible game, it could have been much worse, and the game is most certainly playable.  It seems balanced (at the time of the review) and I have yet to encounter a real problem space that I simply could not finish.  I will complain though, that I have yet to discover a way to flee a combat.  Which I find to be in poor taste... there is simply no way I have found to disengage from a fight once something closes the distance etoo you.  So I would suggest to be VERY careful.  Makes you think actually, which is a good thing in a manner of speaking.  Unfortunately, some fights you will not know you can't deal with until you start the fight, so save often.is the game worth getting?  Currently, I am totally torn.  The super fan of this genre is willing to accept even a mediocre title, and invest.  The game itself is not above 30 dollars in charge, but at the same time I am torn to say that you should wait till it goes on sale before picking it up.  Why get a game from a big company, when you can get a great game from a smaller indie company... (go get legend of Grimmrock)  If you are a true blue fan of might and magic, and you want another dungeon crawl to add to your list, then by all means, the game is not unplayably bad.  But just understand, that you are supporting what seems to me, like a cash cow attempt to milk the might and magic license from your friends at Ubi-soft.If the late game is terrible, then I will add to the review, if it is good, I will also add to the review later.  Till then, I will, sort of recommend this game to folks.  Just watch my vids and see if you like what you get."
,Recommended,238750,11573271,"Posted: 6 August, 2014",all,Xaneorath,"With Might & Magic 5 being the first game I ever played on an PC and with being a great fan of the series ever since, I saw the release of this title with a smile and a tear.A smile because I had hopes of a good series to be revived, a tear, because I was afraid of how it might turn out.The latest installment of the Heroes of M&M Franchise kind of depressed me, because it was ""over-optimized"" from my point of view. Reduction of Ressources, Conversion of towns, lack of map dwellings, obvious map patterns and the free skilltree gave me the impression of a very monotonous game, where good improvements like the bosses, an interesting story or the big maps couldn't completly save it for me.But what about Might & Magic X now?I have to admit, when I first saw the screenshots, I was scared off. Partly because of the bad impressions of HoMM mentioned earlier, partly because I saw the reused Models. It made me worry about a cheaply produced game with repitative ressources.However. I was wrong!Right now Im halfway through the game, and it really manages to bring back that positive Dungeon-Crawler-Feeling the past series excelled at. The reused models dont annoy me as much, as I like to watch the fine details on the animations up close, whereas in the far away top-down perspective of HoMM one might have missed a lot. I realize how being able to reuse so much, the developers could focus more on the other aspects of the game, like the gameworld, dungeons and such.(Besides reused ressources actualy being a very sustainable way of game development)The Difficulty ""Warrior"" gives me, a very well challenged game, with a precisly adjusted curve of improving enemy stacks, as well as the obligatory ""come back when you feel ready"" challenges on the way.The skills and abilities are well thought through, and invite you to change your tactics accordingly when fighting different constellations of enemies.Of course, it is less story/decision-driven as The Witcher or Dragon Age and more focused on battles group VS group, but thats just the good old Might&Magic Series for you. And from my point of view, it is a nice addition to the current array of RPGs.One last thing: I do not know about the stability on other systems, but it tends to crash for me. A lot. It started when I entered Act II and since then I crashed ~7 Times with one ""freeze of death"".Luckily a thing you can avoid if you just Quicksave often, and also many crashes seem to happen right after changing a map, after the Autosave is done. Still you gotta have the nerves for it. ;)This is a definite recommendation from me. Buy it, and experience the well done newest installment of a series, which I daresay influenced the path of many a RPG gamer."
