,Recommended,238750,9076542,"Posted: 12 February, 2014",all,Flutterz,"As someone who only played one other game in the series, Might and Magic 8, Legacy feels to me as both a nostalgia trip and a game which tries a bit too much to be similar to previous games in the series to be its own game, but too little to be a remake.The most obvious differences between 8 and Legacy are that the former is semi-turn-based with free movement and the ability to swap out any party member except the leader, while the latter is completely turn-based with grid-based movement and your party is fixed from the start which, as far as I know, is what the series was like up to around the 6th game.The biggest disappointments in Legacy are that the game is significantly more linear than 8, and the world is significantly smaller. A large part of the enjoyment of Might and Magic, to me, was exploring new locations, seeing how quickly enemies can annihilate me, then finding ways to sneak or fly past the enemies and try to acquire the loot they are protecting. However now most enemies you encounter will be roughly as powerful as you are because new towns are unlocked only as you progress through the main quest, as opposed to them all being available from the start, the starter island notwithstanding. And if you do encounter enemies that are more powerful than you, which is either in mini-dungeons that simply have 1 very powerful monster, or, more rarely, on the world map, you may as well simply reload your most recent save, because once combat begins it is impossible to escape, save for perhaps some spell I have not yet discovered.There are also a couple of mechanics which are nearly pointless given how the game is structured, namely the fact that trainers for skills are scattered around the world and buying a ride to another city. In 8 trainers for skills could be in any of the several towns or out in the wilderness, particularly if they're the highest rank trainer, and if you looked and asked around you could generally get to the trainer no matter where he was, because even if he was in the highest-level town, you could simply get a ride there and find the trainer, despite the fact that a single step outside would spell your doom. But since you cannot move on to the next town without completing a number of quests, for balance reasons the trainers are much more cluttered. Nearly every rank 1 trainer is in the starting town, most of the rank 2 trainers are in the second town, and after exploring for about an hour I've found 3 rank 3 trainers pretty close to each other in the wilderness. As a result all that's left of a mechanic that encouraged exploration is the requirement to walk all around town until you find the right house, as well as limiting your skill progression if you haven't gotten far enough through the storyline. In a similar vein, buying a ride to another town is essentially pointless as it only takes a minute or two of walking to cover the distance on foot.I also have a few more minor complaints. There is no tavern card game, which was a great time-waster as well as an interesting way to get some artifacts, and there are barely any traps in any of the dungeons, whereas in 8 nearly half of all chests were booby-trapped and taking one wrong step could lead to ambushes, fireballs or even falling into a pit of snakes.Despite these complaints, I've enjoyed my time with the game so far. While not as much as in the game I played all those years ago, exploring is fun as is slaughtering weaker monsters and barely defeating monsters that are more powerful than you. The grid-based movement, while more restricting, also means that you can't defeat monsters that are significantly more powerful than you simply by kiting them or by flying above them while they gather underneath, vainly trying to reach you. Similarly, while the fact that your party cannot be changed after you start means you can't be as versatile with your group of adventurers, it also means you can't simply cast an invisibility spell at level 10, sneak through a cave full of high-level dragons and recruit a level 50 dragon into your party. It's a different experience to Might and Magic 8, but a fun one nonetheless."
