76561198027983346,Recommended,238750,32835615,Posted: 26 June,all,Fruit Basket,"TL;DR - If You like old-school cRPGs, buy this on a sale.As a fan of the series (started with VI, but played pretty much every part), I rejoiced when I've learned that Ubi greenlit a game from a series and genre I've presumed dead. That being said, I acknowledge the fact, that this game is neither the best M&M game nor the best retro-style cRPG. Nevertheless, if you're a fan of the series, or liked Legends of Grimrock, or other similar titles, this one is fun too.It's rather minimalistic with only three classes and four races, but each race+class combo is treated differently (e.g an Orc warrior is an aggressive Barbarian, whereas a Dwarf is tanky Shieldbearer, and a Human Crusader has some healing abilities) and as the game progresses they get different special skills. Movement is grid based like in M&M I through V, and everything is turn based (enemies won't move, unless your party moved/waited) and the combat, while rather simple, is a snap, once you know what you're doing. The story is quite standard (find four magical thingies to save the world), and is set in the HoMM VI universe, although prior knowledge of that game is not necessary. Nothing special, but it does harken back to an age when cRPGs were simpler, and like I've said, if you liked that kind of games, this one emulates them very nicely, with more contemporary graphics.Also, I never had any game breaking bugs, that seem to plague other players, although the game is poorly optimized, and after an hour or so the framerate drops significantly."
