76561198017197756,Not Recommended,238750,9406220,"Posted: 9 March, 2014",all,Alexander,"ConsHorribly long load times, easily 15-30 seconds for an area.  There are cases where if you want to run back to town, you will need to run through 4+ areas.  With movement and load times this can take easily five minutes.  Too make it even more annoying the loading of an area STOPS if the screen loses focus, so no alt-tabbing during a load time.This is simply too immersion breaking.   There is a good chance you will hit a point where you have to run back to town realize this could easily involve five minutes to get there and then ANOTHER five minutes to get back.  If you’re the type of person who will drop this game and forget it with the above scenario don’t buy it.ProsProbably the best combat system for a turn based RPG I’ve seen in a long time.Melee for example you have the three styles, duel-wield, shield and two-hander each one has situations where one is better.  A monster has the ability vindictive, for every miss on him he gets one more hit, which might damages your whole party.  Duel wielding dagger wielders with 4 attacks might get you killed if they miss too often one round, while a two handers one swing mass damage won’t cause a wipe.   Conversely a monster might be able to block the first swing against him 75% of the time, making the duel wielder at worst lose one attack and the two-hander do none.The spells are just as varied and important as well with their effects frequently being more important than their damage.   Pushing a monster square away, putting a monster to sleep, reducing the number of attacks a monster gets, buffing the party, removing block attempts or armour from monsters, AoE spells, and many more effects.Although some fights do break down into a simple damage race, knowing what type of melee and spell to use and the correct order actually matters in this game."
76561198031579361,Recommended,238750,11110937,"Posted: 6 July, 2014",all,mkucharski,"The game has performance issues, especially around the 680gtx cards. Only uses the first card, and will pretty much peg it most of the game (bug). But the game is fun, and captures the original feel of might and magic 3-5.  The game is pretty well balances, difficult but most party combinations have a way to beat it. The Falchon and the Unicorn is very difficult, I got through the jail to the palace courtyard. after 100+ attempts I finally modded my archemage (which was healer/area dps) ac by 25, and vitality by 20 through gear  modifications. I also increased my warmongers ac by 25. This kept my whole party from being one hit and allowed my only healer to resurrect. I still had quite a challenge to get to the end, but at least it wasnt impossible. I am sure there are party and gear combinations that make it beatable but when you face 20+ enemies all capable of one shot kills (with several that can 1 shot party kill), with facing 6 at a time, it is very little odds that you will get lucky enough to survive. The one time I did, I had to reload because I couldn't resurrect my party.  If you mod start small, even 10% might be enough to make the difference.  I recommend it, its a fun old school rpg, but only if you like extreme challenges tackle falchon and the unicorn (or opt for some mods) don't mod before the dlc, it will ruin your whole experience the main game is well balanced."
