76561197976308753,Recommended,238750,8835874,"Posted: 24 January, 2014",all,Flyingflea,"After some installing issues and finishing the game, I can give a proper review.Initially I had problems running the game after install; which I fixed by forcing Administrator Rights in Windows.  Before this, the game would crash with an error report every single time.  This took several hours of trial-and-error, during which I was not very happy.Having not played any of the other series before this one, I can say that the combat style is turned based, similar to say... Final Fantasy 7 turned-based.  Navigation through the world is tile-based, which I didn't like or dislike; since the graphic scenery was consistently believable enough.  There are some load time issues while traversing the world and I was getting bad frame rates in some areas.  The graphics are mostly above-average but occasionally there are some very poorly textured objects.I did not find any game-ending bugs but there were some plot-line bugs and companion NPC's  working incorrectly like the Negotiator NPC not giving the proper discount for goods.Plot-wise & quest-wise, the game held my attention enough for me to complete it from start to end.  I took my time finishing the game and even restarted several times to test out new class combinations.  It honestly took me about a week to finish but- as I said- I was learning the game and restarting several times.  There is a hard starting condition where your party has practically nothing and needs everything to survive- new equipment, new spells, new general knowledge to learn about the surrounding area, and a tide of quests to complete.  This is the funnest part of the game for me, due to the difficulty.  About mid-game it becomes apparent that your characters have every inventory slot filled (some with uber-powerful relics), necessary spells purchased & learned, with skill trees grand-mastered--- and while I would have liked the enemies, especially the bosses, to scale they did not.  A lot of the boss fights towards end game were simply the same exact spell casting order that I used to kill the lesser enemies on the plains.  This is when the difficulty practically tapers off.  Towards the end-game I distinctly remember several boss battles where I stayed at range and casted the same 2 ranged spells by my mages; meanwhile the boss couldn't even out-damage the base-line regen spell cast at the start of battle.  The boss inevitably dies to simple attrition and I get an uber relic.  Battles like this are stress-free and the most relaxing battles ever fought, but the fun-factor suffers greatly.After finishing the game I think the final score lies somewhere between around 80/100.  Due to bugs I might drop that score down a bit since there are a lot of bugs that need to be addressed.  Then again, the asking price is what makes the game worthwhile at a little over $20 so regardless a score of 80 feels justified.  It is a thumbs-up."
