,Recommended,238750,16855900,"Posted: 2 July, 2015",all,scottryman,"Pros:- Lots of spells, weapons, armor, and items to satisfy your cravings for treasure.- Engaging and clever puzzles.- Tactical combat that is easy to pick up, but still provides a challenge.- Solid story with characters Might & Magic fans may find familiar.- Simplified level system from previous games.Cons:- uPlay required (They do give you some extras when you use uPlay units though. I don't like it, but at least they give you some nice extras for it).- Slow to load, some objects don't appear properly (several shrubs appeared in the middle of a fight where there were no shrubs/foliage at first a couple times. Not a deal breaker, just a little weird).- There is a glitch that corrupts your save file (If this happens, don't erase your old game! Start a new one and enter the first dungeon. Then, when the game autosaves when you've entered, load your old game!)- Grid movement system isn't for everybody (though the old free movement system from 6,7, & 8 was a little wonky, so do what you like).All in all, highly recommended."
,Not Recommended,238750,17625869,"Posted: 20 August, 2015",all,redwizard000,"Wow what a horrible game... The graphics are extremely dated, and not in a charming way (this game came out in 2014? srsly? Oblivion came out in 2006 and its graphics blow this away!). I have seen indy titles with better graphics and effects, I expect more from an AAA studio. The interface is clunky, wtf is up with the weird ""tile based"" movement system? You are stuck on a grid?!? What is this? Might and Magic II? MM6, 7, 8 and 9 had no problem letting the party freely move and look around, you toggled ""turn based mode"" on and off when needed. This game locks it on runs the world every time you step into the next grid tile (you know the way the old DOS 1-Xeen Might and Magic games did...). The character races, classes and skills are pretty basic and lack the options and depth of the games predicessors. It's like they decided to try to capture the look and feel of old titles but managed to capture all the negative things about them with none of the positive.I haven't played much but I already noticed several assets are recycled from previous games... Mostly sound effects that are from MM6, 7, 8. Several of the jingles, the sound of the quest log opening and closing, the sound of drinking potions are all from the old games. It is laughable and only makes me wish I was replaying one of the old titles.I mean... Might and Magic VIII Day of the Destroyer, a game that came out in the year 2000 had 7 base classes, plus 7 promotion classes, plus the dragons. MMX basically has 3... a ""warrior"" a ""hybrid"" or a ""caster"" and the class is a bit different depending on race. VIII had 35 unique skills, X has 25 and they aren't very creative. Your wizard can't even grand master all of the magic spells. VIII had very distinct magic skills, the 4 elemental magics were for wizards, the three ""self"" magics were for healers and the light\dark were shared (there was also class specific magic...) This game, I am not sure exactly how to distinguish between a healer and a caster, you don't seem to start with any healing spells. The previous few games were cool because you could explore the world freely in real time and then press ""enter"" to go into turn based mode when needed; you didn't feel like you were locked to a rigid grid.Also, dare I say, the graphics are almost better in 6\7\8. I mean sure they are low res pixelated sprite based images mostly but at least the characters wander around in real time, with a walk cycle. Your characters move their lips when they talk (yeah, no one moves their lips at all in X... it is sometimes hard to tell who is talking). It was a bit primative but at least it was easy on the eyes. Even MM3 through Xeen looked good, in a cartoony oldschool DOS way (and in Xeen the characters moved their lips when they spoke.) MM1 and MM2 had crap graphics, grid based game play and you had to draw your own maps (sort of) but they came on 5 1\4 floppies so they get a pass.Plus, no game since 6\7\8 has had the awesome inventory and equipment equip screens that 6\7\8 had. You could actually see what the thing in your inventory looked like and when you put it on your character they actually looked like they were wearing or using that item. MM9 and X went back to the oldschool ""list of items"" method and little squares to put the items in to equip them.6\7\8 had a few animated cutscenes, and they were animated well for their time. This game has an extremely long intro, plus another 10 minutes of naration as soon as the game starts and it is all told with still images and voice overs with characters that can't move their lips.The only thing that X seems to have taken from 6\7\8 is some ripped off audio assets.Add to all of this the ""wonderful"" experience of having to use UPlay... F-ck UPlay. It took quite an effort just to get this game to launch on my PC (among other things I had to sign up for a 3rd UPlay account because for some reason they can't find my old credentials) and - it wasn't worth it.The Might and Magic series peaked with 6, 7 and 8. 9 was OK. X is pretty bad.Go back to remaking ""Heroes"" clones Ubisoft! If this was an Indy title I would cut it some slack but... come on, this is Ubisoft, the guys who brought us Assasins Creed and Far Cry. Ubisoft and Limbic Entertainment are way above ""Indy"" level developers. I haven't been this disapointed with a game with the title Might and Magic since Dark Messiah. These guys are making me start to consider MM9 as one of the ""good"" Might and Magic games... (and I used to hate that game! Well, hate is a strong word. Strongly dislike is more like it.) I miss 3DO and New World Computing. They would have never let this happen.Damn, writing this review has made me want to go back and replay the good Might and Magic games."
