,Not Recommended,238750,21392321,"Posted: 22 February, 2016",all,mike,"Yes I did play many hours, but most of these hours were played with a trainer on the side to help compensate for the insane difficulty imbalance of the game, I really wanted to see if it would get better but it did not really...I've played this type of game for quite a while, that includes Dungeons Master, Eye of the Beholder, the original M&M series (including World of Xeen and then the ""3d"" versions), and more recently Grimrock 1 and 2.It's obvious that the team who worked on the game did not have a huge budget, but they managed to have decent graphics and style all over. My issue is more that they got all the small details wrong:- Hit animations and sounds play *before* the attack dice have been rolled, so basically you see characters die, explosion happen, ...BEFORE the main attack animation has even started. That makes the combat frustrating to say the least.- The characters are talking, which is nice, except it was done very badly: When my warrior is stunned, when my magician is dead, I don't want to hear them complain about whatever happen next or point out that they are tired and that we should sleep.- The design involves a lot of instant death, so basically you have to quick save a lot because your next step may just be the last one, and there was no way to know that. People who call that ""oldskool"" don't know what they are talking about. The olsdkool variant is as deadly, but in general designers left you some hints that you were going to have your♥♥♥♥♥handed to you :p- The loot distribution is abysmal, there's no link between the difficulty of a fight, the fact that the objects are well hidden in a super remote place,... it may still be a pointless non magic item.- The whole RPG system is broken. Skills almost don't matter, all that matters is that you can resist whatever is thrown into your face, which means magic shields and armors, resistance buffs, and protections against stunning, weakness, sleep, etc... the rest does not really matter.- Linking the progression of skills with the story events is so unfair... if you picked up some classes or weapons, you will not be able to level them up until way later in the game because you can't access the trainer you need for the skill.- The inventory system is bad (no auto sorting, no auto selling of the trash loot, you can't throw away stuff if you are looting (you have to close the chest, open the inventory, throw away whatever you wanted, then go back to the chest and finish looting)In conclusion I would say that it was a good attempt tech wise, but that the game design was bad, even the story was just generic fantasy with M&M typical characters while totally missing on the less traditional canon (that involves robots and spaceships.)Try at your own risk."
