,Recommended,238750,10742728,"Posted: 23 June, 2014",all,Valarian,"If you're a fan of the original Might and Magic games (And yes, I do even mean 6, 7, 8 and 9) you'll find many of the elements you enjoyed from those games here: Exploration, riddles, puzzles, and resource management. There are a number of interesting and unique quests which venture out of the normal ""go here, kill this, gather that"" formula, the best of which actually make an active effort to draw you into the lore of Ashan.If you're concerned about the grid-based movement, or the relatively small size of the game, don't be. The developers know better than to get in over their head on a risky and much-beloved franchise. It may be small in scope, but I find it to be structurally tight and sound -- in the narrative/game mechanic sense, at least. There are a number of bugs that plague the game, but nothing that's really kept me from enjoying it.The combat is frustrating in that you can't really run or reposition your party, but the resource management aspect of it is as satisfying and interesting as it ever has been, and there are still plenty of tactical decisions to be made in the course of your adventure.Better than the originals? Definitely not. But certainly worth a look."
,Recommended,238750,10013473,"Posted: 3 May, 2014",all,Disparrow,"Yo, if you like old school RPGs in the veins of say the Might and Magic series or Lands of Lore you need to get this. It runs on a grid so it's less fluid than Escape from Grimrock (another game that harkens back to the time of old school RPGS), but that gives it an even greater retro charm, hell it even has an option for fuzzy retro graphics. It pays greatest homage to Might and Magic 1-4, it still does give refrences to six and seven (seven being my absolute favorite of the series). It even gives the synopsis of the plots for each previous game in in-game lore books while maintaining the new lore and world.Though character creation is limited to four races with three classes for each race, it's still not as bad as Might Magic XIII's character creation (IDK about you guys but that game had the worst race/class choices in the series). Combat can be a bit buggy at times, the latest patch seems to have fixed a lot of the release issues, so I can now give this game my full approval."
76561198032742896,Recommended,238750,9875941,"Posted: 19 April, 2014",all,woodduck,"If you are old enough to play the old Might and Magic series, and kept going back for more, then Legacy is probably for you. This really is just like playing M&M again, but dressed up for the current PC. Yes, it can be hard, and yes enemies can come at you from all sides, but don't let the haters fool you, this is very fine and worthy successor to those old M&M games. And you certainly get your moneys worth -- the game has many hours of gameplay in it. I am still in Act III and have logged up 30 hours plus.Thoroughly recommended, especially for the more mature gamer out there who remembers what CRPGs were like in the 1980s."
