,Recommended,238750,8957034,"Posted: 2 February, 2014",all,"AJ, Lord of Chaos","-Rewarding old-school experience--First impression-Starting off completely linear for the beginning hours and in the worst graphic setting regardless of card, MMX makes a terrible first impression but I'm glad I persisted - it improves a lot later (also changed the settings). After the second city the game opens up leaving you to choose which side quest to tackle or which way to go.-Battles-Like previous MMs high level enemies may lurk just around a corner and slaughter you so you save/reload a lot while exploring. Even the ""normal"" fights are challenging so if you want to play a cakewalk game this is not for you.Every battle turn you decide whether your PCs cast healing or an elemental shield or weaken the enemy armor, whether to attack or drink a potion. Also the tiles you stand on play a tactical role as you discover by dying to the second boss (yes you will die). Moving into a position where you get flanked can spell your doom and the harder battles have you flanked from all sides.-Other Gameplay-A lot of randomized loot to choose from. No hand-holding like respecing skills or warning if you enter a difficult area beside the ""dangerous caves"". No big spoilers on the automap or arrows pointing at your quest target.Bunch of secret loot caches to find, hidden treasure rooms and powerful relics just like in the past.Also riddle questions, switch, stepping and teleport puzzles and traps. Not always fun but mostly.Along the way you find elemental shards to place on a corresponding altar to trigger a boss fight. This gives you a useful ability like forestwalk, waterwalk or enemy awareness.PC-wise there are 4 races each with 3 exclusive classes (might/magic/hybrid) = 12 classes and seven schools of magic. You only have 2 male and 2 female portraits per race which is rather lazy. You choose 4 dudes for your party. Depending on class you can either not learn a skill at all or expert/master/grandmaster it like the berserker can master ""axe skill"" and grand-master ""spear skill"" but can not learn ""sword"" or ""dagger"" or ""heavy armor"".-Legacy-MMX plays unlike the previous MMs, mostly feels like Wizardry8 meets Worlds of Xeen. It features a lot of easter eggs like a girl who wants to go to the circus like that Nicolai(?) from MM6 or a poem about the destroyer from MM9. Also characters reappear and the shrines to visit on a certain day. Sadly no insta-death fountains anymore.I feel it's a worthy entry to the M&M-franchise which appeared all but finished after the ill-received MM9 and frankly I'm glad they're back.I can recommend this game for fans of complex party-turn-based RPG-games as of old or any RPG-fan who likes a challenge as the game is really entertaining and there is a lot to do and to explore."
76561197988585253,Recommended,238750,9025326,"Posted: 8 February, 2014",all,mech,"A surprisingly good sequel to a classic game series, quite unexpected from Ubisoft to be honest. Just don't expect a cutscene-heavy, ""cinematic"" RPG, MMX is pure gameplay with a very basic story, but a nice balance between open-world exploration and turn-based combat, tons of dungeons, creatures and powerful items to find.This is one of those games that gets the character progression just right - you feel really helpless in the beginning, struggling to kill a bunch of wolves without someone dying, and the game stays difficult until the end (on warrior difficulty), but in the end, once your characters have earned their promotions and have got grandmaster ranks, they finally begin to feel powerful, annihilating hordes of monsters with a few spells, which feels really satisfying.One thing that I didn't like about the combat mechanics was that once you enter melee range there is no way to move around, and no way whatsoever to escape from a bad encounter. Because there is a lot of exploration involved, and because even the starting area contains some creatures that are unbeatable until much later, this results in frequent save/load abuse. Scripted ""trapped"" chests or doors that cause enemies to spawn behind your back are also quite lame for the same reason, thankfully there are not too many of those."
