,Recommended,238750,8885088,"Posted: 27 January, 2014",all,GDwarf,"Solid, but not exceptional.I'm a huge fan of Might and Magic IV and V, which Legacy is heavily inspired by. Indeed, in many ways this is almost MMIV/V with 3D graphics, and more text.That said, while MMX is definitely fun, it lacks the sense of humour and scale of its predecessors. MMIV/V had you exploring an entire planet, while Legacy keeps you on a single archapeligo. Despite the fact that there's still lots to explore, this does make everything feel oddly cramped. While the cities in X are about as far apart as those in IV and V, they feel much closer (and there's fewer of 'em). It's a minor issue, really, but it kinda sums up the game: The same as what came before, but somehow cramped.As for the style: The old Might and Magic games didn't take themselves at all seriously. Well over 3/4 of the people you talk to were jokes. X is much more serious. It certainly has jokes, but there are fewer of them, replaced with lots of text. Usually I love lots of text in games, but here there are so many characters and factions to keep track of (and it definitely helps to have played Heroes VI by the same devs and set in the same world) that it becomes hard to really care about them, which is a shame, because the actual plot has loads of potential.All-in-all, it's a buy if you like games such as Legend of Grimrock (though that's real time to MMX's turn based), Etrian Odyssey, or the old Might and Magic titles, then it's well worth a buy. If the idea of slowly working your way through a dungeon where one bad decision or unlucky chance can doom you, then this ain't for you."
