,Recommended,238750,8943874,"Posted: 1 February, 2014",all,Forgetful Brain,"Temper your expectations, and you might enjoy this game. First off, don't think the screenshots on the store page are how it actually looks - I went in thinking it would be a gorgeous dungeon crawler and was severely let down. The game is actually quite hideous, and often looks about ten years too old. Inexplicably, it's also already a frontrunner for the worst optimized game of 2014. It doesn't matter how good your computer is - it will sound like it's about to blast off into space, and the game will chug and chop as you play. It's a shame too, because past all that the game offers quite an enjoyable old-school romp. Gone are the days of free roaming. This is a turn-based first-person RPG on a grid. The story is Fantasy 101, and hardcore fans of the Might and Magic series will probably get more out of it than everyone else. If you're like me, you'll skip the awful NPC dialogue and bash your head against your desk the 100th time your mercenary says, ""Looks like they smelled us - who forgot to take a bath?"" Still, there's some definite satisfaction out of exploring the map, finding legendary artifacts, and encountering enemies that will kill you in one hit (only to come back and faceroll them later on). The game will run around 40 - 60 hours if you want to do all the sidequests. Grab when it's $5 if you're looking for a blast of dungeon-crawling nostalgia - just don't expect it to be a polished or particularly original experience."
76561198011736291,Recommended,238750,8945391,"Posted: 1 February, 2014",all,DanK,"In its own right this is a great game. i had previously played M&M 6,7,and 8, and the game is slightly different from what i had expected. that being said i feel ubisoft did a top notch job on this game. if you enjoyed legend of grimmrock but while playing said ""i want to explore outside"" then this is the game for you. It is far more detailed and refined than grimmrock, and although M&M X isn't without its flaws it is definitely worth every cent."
76561198020656048,Recommended,238750,8948178,"Posted: 2 February, 2014",all,Clawplach32,"I'll preface this by saying this review is indicative of the full game experience (NOT just early access like most of these reviews seem to be for).  I'm a long time Might and Magic fan (yes, that includes the ones before VI!) and from a gameplay standpoint it most certainly delivers.  Here's a quick rundown of the good and bad.BAD-The game is saddled with the dreaded UPlay.  The servers are all over the place (not quite Origin levels) which can be a pain or can be painless depending on which way the wind blows.  That also means the game has some unlockables and achievements and the like, but all accessed through the UPlay client.-The game is buggy as hell.  After several months of 'early access' I expected it to be a little more polished.  It never reaches HOMM6 levels of ridiculousness, and I never had any game-breaking bugs, but there are a lot of graphical glitches and other interesting things that will be seen from even the most powerful machines.-There seems to be some content either missing and/or unfinished in the final product.  I won't spoil anything here but a look at the UPlay achievements indicates a lot of inaccessible material.-Enemies do not respawn and there is no 'respec' option, so it is not completely out of the realm of possibility to paint yourself into a corner.GOOD-Extremely solid and (mostly) fair turn-based combat.  There are a few too many battles that are initiated with enemies spawning on all sides of you, but once you learn to expect it you can get in to most fights fully buffed.-Varied party options and a great deal of spells and skills to take advantage of.  As with all RPGs some are *far* more useful than others but once you nail down a balanced team you can start blasting through monsters with gusto.-Fantastic voice acting and dialogue.  Story sequences are sparse but enjoyable.  The music is also great but sometimes will 'disappear' for long stretches (possibly a bug).-Lengthy quest and a lot of side material.  Doing all the available quests for a party of 4 different classes and exploring the entire world took around 40+ hours for me.-Several callbacks to earlier Might and Magic (as well as Heroes of Might and Magic) installments that will make you miss New World Computing.Overall I very much enjoyed my time with M&MX-Legacy.  Any fans of the early series (1-3 and especially Xeen) will find a lot to like here.  For the rest of you with a passing interest I would advise waiting until either some bug fixes hit or a steam sale to take the plunge."
,Recommended,238750,8948368,"Posted: 2 February, 2014",all,Azradesh,"To true return to RPG goodness. Party make up matters, stat allocation matters, skill choices matter; you actually need to think a little.It's might not be much to look at but this is my favourite game of the last 10 years."
,Recommended,238750,8949443,"Posted: 2 February, 2014",all,n1ckn4m3,"Good throwback to the grid based Might and Magic games like 3, 4, 5 (Isles of Terra, Clouds of Xeen/Darkside of Xeen).  Not the most well optimized game -- it doesn't look extremely good, but it will *bury* a GTX 580 -- when entering shops, my GPU fan shoots to 100% and the card temp goes to 90-95C.  Fairly widespread issue but no acknowledgement from the vendor on their forums.In any case, the game is good -- the story is mindless and may as well be non-existant, unfortunately, but the gameplay is pretty much classic MM.  The smaller party size makes things slightly more strategic as your margin of error has decreased notably, which also helps to contribute to an overall greater difficulty level than the previous.I hope they fix the optimization problems, it's silly that a game that looks like this can load my GPU in ways that Crysis 3 and Far Cry 3 don't, but even if they don't, if you liked the grid / turn based Might and Magic games, this is an easy $25 to spend."
